25|$|The <b>union</b> <b>shop</b> issue came to {{increasingly}} {{dominate the}} WSB's deliberations. Initially, Feinsinger refused to consider any issue other than wage increases. Feinsinger even {{refused to discuss}} the issue with his superior, Putnam. Feinsinger was under pressure to win support for a recommendation by a majority of the Board and issue a report before the union lost patience and struck. CIO and Steelworkers' counsel Arthur Goldberg persuaded the WSB's labor representatives to withhold their support for a recommendation until Feinsinger not only agreed to consider the <b>union</b> <b>shop</b> but recommend it to the president.|$|E
